    </div>
    <d-title class=3D"real-title">
        <h1>Putting up Bumpers</h1>
    </d-title>
   =20
    <figure class=3D"gdoc-image" style=3D"--img-width: 50px; "><img src=3D"=
https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/bumpers.png">
        <figcaption class=3D"text-caption">Image by <a href=3D"https://www.=
flickr.com/photos/a4gpa/2311679637">a4gpa on
                Flickr</a> (CC BY-SA 2.0)</figcaption>
    </figure><d-article>
        <div class=3D"section-authors" data-author=3D"Samuel R. Bowman" dat=
a-published=3D"April 23, 2025"></div>

        <div style=3D"position: relative">
            <span class=3D"tldr">tl;dr</span>
            <p>Even if we can't solve alignment, we can solve the problem o=
f catching and fixing misalignment.</p>

        </div>
        <div style=3D"border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); width: 1=
00%; margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0;"></div>


        <p>If a child is bowling for the first time, and they just aim at t=
he pins and throw, they=E2=80=99re almost certain to
            miss. Their ball will fall into one of the gutters. But if ther=
e were beginners=E2=80=99 bumpers in place blocking
            much of the length of those gutters, their throw would be almos=
t certain to hit at least a few pins. This
            essay describes an alignment strategy for early AGI systems I c=
all =E2=80=98putting up bumpers=E2=80=99, in which we <span style=3D"font-w=
eight: 700;">treat it as a top priority to implement and test safeguards th=
at </span><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">allow us to course-correct if w=
e turn out to have built or deployed a
                misaligned model</span>, in the same way that bowling bumpe=
rs allow a poorly aimed ball to reach its
            target.</p>
        <p>To do this, we'd aim to build up many largely-independent lines =
of defense that allow us to catch and respond
            to early signs of misalignment. This would involve significantl=
y improving and scaling up our use of tools
            like mechanistic interpretability audits, behavioral red-teamin=
g, and early post-deployment monitoring.&nbsp;We
            believe that, even without further breakthroughs, this work we =
can almost entirely mitigate the risk that we
            unwittingly put misaligned circa-human-expert-level agents in a=
 position where they can cause severe harm.
        </p>
        <p>On this view, if we=E2=80=99re dealing with an early AGI system =
that has human-expert-level capabilities in at least
            some key domains, our approach to alignment might look somethin=
g like this:</p>
        <ol>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Pretraining: </span>We start with a
                pretrained base model.</li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Finetuning: </span>We attempt to fine-tune
                that model into a helpful, harmless, and honest agent using=
 some combination of human preference data,
                <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/constitutiona=
l-ai-harmlessness-from-ai-feedback">Constitutional
                    AI</a>-style model-generated preference data, outcome r=
ewards, and present-day forms of scalable
                oversight.
            </li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Audits as our Primary Bumpers: </span>At
                several points during this process, we perform <a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.anthropic.com/research/auditing-hidden-objectives">alignment aud=
its</a>&nbsp;on the
                system under construction, using many methods in parallel. =
We=E2=80=99d draw on mechanistic interpretability,
                prompting outside the human/assistant frame, etc.</li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Hitting the Bumpers: </span>If we see signs
                of misalignment=E2=80=94perhaps warning signs&nbsp;for <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/reward-tampering">generalized rew=
ard-tampering</a>&nbsp;or <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/ali=
gnment-faking">alignment-faking</a>=E2=80=94we attempt to
                quickly, approximately identify the cause.</li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Bouncing Off: </span>We rewind our finetuning
                process&nbsp;as far as is needed to make another attempt at=
 aligning the model, taking advantage of what
                we=E2=80=99ve learned in the previous step. </li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Repeat</span><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">: </span>We repeat this =
process until we=E2=80=99ve developed a complete system
                that appears, as best we can tell, to be well aligned. Or, =
we are <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">repeatedly</span>&nbsp;failing i=
n consistent ways, change plans and try to
                articulate as best we can why alignment doesn=E2=80=99t see=
m tractable.</li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Post-Deployment Monitoring as Secondary
                    Bumpers: </span>We then begin rolling out the system in=
 earnest, both for internal R&amp;D and external
                use, but keep substantial monitoring measures in place that=
 provide additional opportunities to catch
                misalignment. If we observe substantial warning signs for m=
isalignment, we return to step 4.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The hypothesis behind&nbsp;the <em>Bumpers</em> approach is that=
, on short timelines (i) this process is <span style=3D"font-style: italic;=
">fairly</span>&nbsp;likely to converge, after a reasonably small number of
            iterations, at an end state in which we are no longer observing=
 warning signs for misalignment and (ii) if
            it converges, the resulting model is very likely to be aligned =
in the relevant sense. </p>
        <p>We are not certain of this hypothesis, but we think it=E2=80=99s=
 important to consider. It has already motivated
            major parts of Anthropic=E2=80=99s safety research portfolio an=
d we=E2=80=99re hiring across several teams=E2=80=94two of them
            new=E2=80=94to build out work along these lines.</p><br><br><br=
>
        <hr><br><br>
        <h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">Introduction</span></h2>
        <p>We are plausibly within a couple of years of developing models t=
hat could automate much of the work of AI
            R&amp;D. This makes <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/resear=
ch/sabotage-evaluations">sabotage and
                sandbagging</a>&nbsp;threat models=E2=80=94where the models=
 deliberately interfere with their own safety measures or
            hide dangerous capabilities=E2=80=94worth addressing soon: If w=
e are to rely substantially on <a href=3D"https://openai.com/index/introduc=
ing-superalignment/">automated alignment research</a>, these are
            the systems that will take on the first load-bearing autonomous=
 alignment projects.<sup><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bu=
mpers/#ftnt1" id=3D"ftnt_ref1">[1]</a></sup>&nbsp;If these models are thems=
elves well aligned, our work gets much easier
            past that point. If these models are misaligned in a way that m=
otivates them to sabotage or sandbag, then at
            best, we will pay enormous opportunity costs from our inability=
 to trust our best tools, and at worst, we
            will foolishly trust them and thereby allow them to sabotage ou=
r work in ways we fail to notice or unwind.
        </p>
        <p>Ideally, before this point, we would have a thorough understandi=
ng of the empirical landscape surrounding AI
            alignment: If we run our alignment process and it appears to su=
cceed, we should be <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">confident</span>&nb=
sp;that the model is in fact aligned. </p>
        <p>There are few research problems in the world that compare in imp=
ortance to the problem of gaining this
            understanding (and many of the problems that <span style=3D"fon=
t-style: italic;">do</span>&nbsp;compare in
            importance involve AGI safety in some way). But it=E2=80=99s un=
likely that we=E2=80=99ll succeed to an adequate degree in
            time, and it=E2=80=99s even less likely that we=E2=80=99ll <spa=
n style=3D"font-style: italic;">know</span>&nbsp;we=E2=80=99ve succeeded:
            Solving this problem definitively could easily take many years,=
 but because of the <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/news/the-case-for-=
targeted-regulation">current paucity of frontier
                regulation</a>, the competitive nature of the industry, and=
 the immense potential upsides of deploying
            powerful AI for both safety research and <a href=3D"https://www=
.darioamodei.com/essay/machines-of-loving-grace">the world at large</a>, we=
 can=E2=80=99t count
            on being able to wait that long to start using these early AGI =
systems.</p>
        <p>Despite all this, I expect that we can still muddle through with=
out this kind of deep understanding in a way
            that nonetheless makes a good outcome likely. </p>
        <p>Bumpers is the high-level plan that I argue AGI-focused alignmen=
t
            research efforts should largely prioritize instead=E2=80=94the =
way that I expect we muddle through. It relies on a
            key hypothesis about our situation:</p>
        <ol>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Detection of misalignment seems
                    tractable</span><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">:</sp=
an>&nbsp;If an early AGI system is misaligned enough
                to cause unrecoverable harm, it seems likely that there is =
some known technique that could be used to
                determine that it is misaligned before this takes place=E2=
=80=94perhaps, but not necessarily, before deployment.
            </li>
        </ol>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">If this is false, attempting t=
o run the iterative process above will not
                prevent us from unwittingly placing a misaligned model in a=
 position where it can cause severe harm.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>Further, the claim that this plan should be a top priority for A=
GI developers<span style=3D"font-style: italic;">&nbsp;</span>relies on thr=
ee more claims: </p>
        <ol>
            <li value=3D"2" style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"fon=
t-weight: 700;">Alignment is not clearly trivial:
                </span>Ordinary attempts to align early AGI systems could p=
lausibly produce a misaligned result. </li>
        </ol>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">If this is false, and we know =
that it is false, then Bumpers work is a waste
                of effort and a cause of
                potentially-costly delays.<sup><a href=3D"https://alignment=
.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftnt2" id=3D"ftnt_ref2">[2]</a></sup></li>
        </ul>
        <ol>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;" value=3D"3"><span style=3D"fon=
t-weight: 700;">Alignment is likely to be
                    tractable:
                </span>The best current evidence suggests that existing app=
lied alignment techniques like RLHF and <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.co=
m/research/constitutional-ai-harmlessness-from-ai-feedback">Constitutional
                    AI</a>&nbsp;can, <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">at=
 least under ideal circumstances</span>,<span style=3D"font-style: italic;"=
>&nbsp;</span>be used to adequately align early AGI systems. While we may n=
ot
                fully understand what we=E2=80=99re doing when we align a m=
odel, we don=E2=80=99t need to achieve any deep breakthroughs
                in order to succeed in practice. </li>
        </ol>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">If this is false, Bumpers work=
 can
                still carry enormous value by surfacing early evidence that=
 it is false. This evidence can then drive
                both newly-focused research investments and newly-concrete =
public communication about risks. However the
                emphasis on using the bumpers to <span style=3D"font-style:=
 italic;">quickly </span><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">iterate</span>=
&nbsp;on our alignment techniques is misplaced in these
                situations.</li>
        </ul>
        <ol>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;" value=3D"4"><span style=3D"fon=
t-weight: 700;">Alignment theory is not tractable
                    in the
                    short term:</span>&nbsp;We are unlikely to understand m=
isalignment risk well enough in the short term to
                be able to reliably predict whether some specific attempt t=
o align a model is going to succeed.</li>
        </ol>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">If this is false, Bumpers work
                represents a clumsy and uncertain way to solve a critical p=
roblem that we could solve with greater
                confidence by other means.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This is not a costless choice: The Bumpers worldview largely giv=
es
            up on the ability to make highly-confident, principled argument=
s for safety, and it comes with real risks. A
            trial-and-error approach that relies on the same set of tests m=
any times will start to create selection
            pressure that undermines those tests. Further, some possible fo=
rms of misalignment would result in systems
            that actively attempt to subvert our bumpers.</p>
        <p>I nonetheless expect that we could implement a half-dozen or so =
bumpers in such a way that no model (in the
            relevant capability regime) can subvert all of them at once. Th=
is is not guaranteed, but it=E2=80=99s the best
            available option if capabilities progress continues to move as =
quickly as we are anticipating here.</p>
        <p>The hypotheses above are distinct from any normative claim about=
 what level of confidence we should aim to
            have in the safety of a system before we deploy and use it, at =
least in the short term: Under most plausible
            levels of confidence an AI developer might be able to reach in =
the near future, for the capabilities regime
            we target, it will be easier to reach that level of confidence =
by prioritizing the building and testing
            bumpers than by building out a deeper science of alignment that=
=E2=80=99s aimed at more decisively solving the
            problem.</p><br><br><br>
        <h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">What Are the Bumpers?</span><=
/h2>
        <p>There are many methods that could plausibly detect misalignment =
during pre-deployment testing, with varying
            degrees of present day maturity, such as: </p>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Manual <span style=3D"font-wei=
ght: 700;">expert red-teaming</span>, including:
            </li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">Honeypot environments that mim=
ic opportunities to interfere with human
                control, potentially building on real-world data</li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;"><a href=3D"https://www.anthrop=
ic.com/research/auditing-hidden-objectives">Non-assistant
                    persona</a>&nbsp;interviews</li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;"><a href=3D"https://www.alignme=
ntforum.org/posts/GE6pcmmLc3kdpNJja/fuzzing-llms-sometimes-makes-them-revea=
l-their-secrets">Activation
                    fuzzing</a>, steering, and similar methods of injecting=
 variation into model reasoning</li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">High-volume <span style=3D"fon=
t-weight: 700;"><a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2202.03286">automated red-=
teaming</a></span>&nbsp;to look for jailbreaks
                and other unusual triggers of bad behavior</li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;"><a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/auditing-hidden-objective=
s">Interpretability
                        audits</a></span>&nbsp;to look for internal represe=
ntations related to deception or misaligned goals
            </li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Automatic <span style=3D"font-=
weight: 700;">consistency audits</span>&nbsp;to look
                for strategic biases in model behavior, like systematically=
 omitting certain types of information from
                summaries, or doing the same coding task in suspiciously di=
fferent ways when the stated purpose is
                different</li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">This could include scalable-ov=
ersight-style methods that can identify where a
                model=E2=80=99s behavior is most likely to diverge from wha=
t <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">the
                    model</span>&nbsp;would endorse on reflection<sup><a hr=
ef=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftnt3" id=3D"ftnt_ref3"=
>[3]</a></sup></li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><a href=3D"https://ai-alignmen=
t.com/mechanistic-anomaly-detection-and-elk-fb84f4c6d0dc">Mechanistic
                    anomaly detection</a>, probes, and <span style=3D"font-=
weight: 700;">other
                    model-internals-based</span><span style=3D"font-weight:=
 700;">&nbsp;methods</span>&nbsp;for catching shifts in
                behavior</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Beyond these, there are additional methods that can be put in pl=
ace after deployment that may be able to
            catch warning signs of misalignment in the wild before any seri=
ous irreversible harm takes place. These
            secondary defenses include:</p>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Real-time monitoring</span>, human
                rapid-response measures, and related deployment-time AI con=
trol measures<sup><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#=
ftnt4" id=3D"ftnt_ref4">[4]</a></sup>&nbsp;to catch and block acutely misal=
igned behavior</li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">This could include the continu=
ed use of <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">anomaly detection </span>relate=
d white-box methods<span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">&nbsp;</span>that have=
 access to the model=E2=80=99s internal computation</li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Summarization-based <span styl=
e=3D"font-weight: 700;">batch
                    monitoring</span>&nbsp;(as with <a href=3D"https://www.=
anthropic.com/research/clio">Clio</a>&nbsp;or per-user <a href=3D"https://a=
lignment.anthropic.com/2025/summarization-for-monitoring/">hierarchical sum=
marization
                    methods</a>) to look for more diffuse concerning trends=
</li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Staged rollouts</span>, starting=E2=80=94both
                internally and externally=E2=80=94with specially chosen use=
r populations who you trust to surface issues to you
                and trust <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">not</span>&nb=
sp;to use the system in high-stakes settings</li>
            <li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 70=
0;">Security measures </span>that limit models=E2=80=99
                ability to access internal systems autonomously</li>
        </ul>
        <p>To the <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/reasoning-m=
odels-dont-say-think">limited</a>&nbsp;extent that
            modern reasoning models produce <span style=3D"font-weight: 700=
;">transparent reasoning traces</span>, these
            traces will make several of the methods above, in both categori=
es, more effective.</p>
        <p>No one of these methods, under realistic circumstances, will be =
robust enough to rely on. However, even a
            half dozen of these methods, each implemented to the standard o=
f a substantial production effort at an AGI
            developer, should be sufficient to detect potentially-catastrop=
hic forms of misalignment in any plausible
            early AGI system. </p>
        <p>A system that was <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">trying </s=
pan>to evade all of these bumpers would face
            immense obstacles, at least within the capability regime we tar=
get. Such a system would have to be able to
            take intentional, harmful actions with neither its human-access=
ible internal feature representations nor its
            written reasoning traces ever hinting at that intention, even u=
nder extensive red-teaming that can
            manipulate its inputs and internal states in arbitrary ways. It=
 would need to be able to distinguish real
            opportunities to act from our many artificial test cases. If re=
cent trends in model design continue, it also
            would need to do this without being able to do much more active=
 reasoning&nbsp;<span style=3D"font-style: italic;">within its forward pass=
 </span>than happens in present-day models. It would
            need to do all of this in a setting where it is not substantial=
ly superhuman, such that humans are routinely
            (though not continuously) spot-checking its work.</p><br><br><b=
r>

        <h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">Hitting the Bumpers and Bounc=
ing Off</span></h2>
        <p>If we encounter a warning sign that represents reasonably clear =
evidence that some common practice will lead
            to danger, the next step is to try to infer the proximate cause=
. &nbsp;These efforts need not result in a
            comprehensive theory of all of the misalignment risk factors th=
at arose in the training run, but it should
            give us <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">some</span>&nbsp;si=
gnal about what sort of response would treat the
            cause of the misalignment rather than simply masking the first =
symptoms.</p>
        <p>This could look like reading RL logs, looking through training d=
ata or tasks, running evals across multiple
            training checkpoints, running finer-grained or more expensive v=
ariants of the bumper that caught the issue
            in the first place, and <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">per=
haps </span>running small newly-designed
            experiments to check our understanding. Mechanistic interpretab=
ility tools and related training-data
            attribution tools like <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/res=
earch/influence-functions">influence
                functions</a>&nbsp;in particular can give us clues as to wh=
at data was most responsible for the behavior. In
            easy cases, the change might be as simple as redesigning the re=
ward function for some automatically-graded
            RL environment or removing a tranche of poorly-labeled human da=
ta.&nbsp;</p>
        <p>Once we=E2=80=99ve learned enough here that we=E2=80=99re able t=
o act, we then make whatever&nbsp;change to our finetuning process
            seems most likely to solve the problem. Unless the warning sign=
 also calls into question the continuing
            effectiveness&nbsp;of our suite of bumpers,<sup><a href=3D"http=
s://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftnt5" id=3D"ftnt_ref5">[5]</a></=
sup>&nbsp;we finally proceed
            to retrain the
            model as much as seems necessary to mitigate the issue and atte=
mpt a new deployment.</p>
        <p>In addition, by this point, we will likely have learned some rep=
eatable lessons, which we should share
            externally. This is both to allow other developers to avoid enc=
ountering the same danger themselves and to
            allow governments to respond in full knowledge of the risk.</p>
        <p>As a limited early example from our real model development lifec=
ycle: Our evaluations of partially-trained
            versions of Claude 3.7, as described in the <a href=3D"https://=
assets.anthropic.com/m/785e231869ea8b3b/original/claude-3-7-sonnet-system-c=
ard.pdf">System
                Card</a>, found&nbsp;signs of reward hacking on code tasks =
that we were able to partially<sup><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.c=
om/2025/bumpers/#ftnt6" id=3D"ftnt_ref6">[6]</a></sup>&nbsp;mitigate with a=
djustments to our standard finetuning
            techniques.</p>
        <br><br><br>

        <h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">Defending Key Premises</span>=
</h2>
        <h3>Detection of Misalignment Seems Tractable</h3>
        <p>The findings of our recent&nbsp;Auditing paper suggests that, at=
 least under the relatively favorable
            circumstances of our first major trial, there are a several ind=
ependent methods involving (among other
            things) dictionary learning and non-assistant persona prompting=
 that can reveal important facts about a
            model=E2=80=99s alignment that are not readily observable in or=
dinary behavioral testing.</p>
        <p>More broadly, we have seen essentially no naturally-occurring ca=
ses to date where a model is misaligned in
            ways that clearly could not have been caught by thorough pre-de=
ployment testing that includes methods like
            these. To the partial but nontrivial extent that existing inter=
pretability techniques give us a view into
            model cognition, what we=E2=80=99re finding seems much more con=
sistent with the hypothesis that models are
            approximating what we trained them to do in reasonable ways tha=
n that they are subtly acting against us.
            When we do see misalignment, it generally seems to be a consequ=
ence of contingent, understandable errors in
            our training strategies. </p>
        <p>It is not clear that this should continue to be the case. (And s=
ee <a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ceil">Hitting t=
he Capability
                Ceiling</a>&nbsp;below for more discussion of how alignment=
 might cease to be tractable in this sense.) But
            it seems like a fairly likely default&nbsp;outcome, and as such=
, it should be among our top priorities to
            continue to build out and stress-test these detection methods.<=
/p>
        <h3>Alignment Seems Tractable but not Trivial</h3>
        <p>We have not yet failed badly at alignment.&nbsp;Current frontier=
 systems have been deployed widely without this
            surfacing any deep divergences from the intentions of their dev=
elopers of the kind we contemplate here.
            Something like this degree of alignment in an early AGI system,=
 coupled with good progress on task
            elicitation that I expect to emerge from more capabilities-orie=
nted R&amp;D,<sup><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#=
ftnt7" id=3D"ftnt_ref7">[7]</a></sup>&nbsp;should be sufficient to safely b=
egin deploying. </p>
        <p>Current frontier systems also have few or no deep, consistent li=
mitations that prevent them in principle from
            acting as human-level autonomous researchers: We expect that th=
e difference between today=E2=80=99s systems and
            these future systems with these capabilities will be more a dif=
ference in degree than a difference in kind.
            As such, we find it plausible that a similar degree of alignmen=
t can be attained by basically similar means.
        </p>
        <p>However, we know that standard alignment techniques <span style=
=3D"font-style: italic;">can </span>fail,
            sometimes in reasonably subtle ways. Many recent results, inclu=
ding <a href=3D"https://www.emergent-misalignment.com/">Emergent Misalignme=
nt</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/alignment-faking">Ali=
gnment Faking</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/reward-tam=
pering">Sycophancy to Subterfuge</a>, <a href=3D"https://openreview.net/for=
um?id=3DxJljiPE6dg">Wen et al.</a>=E2=80=99s, and <a href=3D"https://cdn.op=
enai.com/pdf/34f2ada6-870f-4c26-9790-fd8def56387f/CoT_Monitoring.pdf">Baker=
 et
                al.</a>=E2=80=99s suggest that some ways of using current s=
tandard techniques can lead to misaligned models
            which attempt to subvert human control. At least some of these =
types of failure plausibly become more
            challenging to avoid as models become more capable. Our challen=
ge, on the Bumpers&nbsp;view, is to build many
            redundant ways of catching and
            correcting this when it occurs.</p>
        <p>In the language of our <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/news=
/core-views-on-ai-safety">Core Views on AI
                Safety</a>&nbsp;post, the Bumpers&nbsp;approach is primaril=
y targeting
            =E2=80=98intermediate-difficulty=E2=80=99 scenarios for alignme=
nt, where alignment is tractable but not trivial. In those
            scenarios, this approach allows us to chart a course to success=
fully deploying an aligned model. However, we
            expect it to also be valuable, to a lesser extent, in many plau=
sible harder worlds where this work could
            provide the evidence we need about the dangers that lie ahead.<=
/p><br><br><br>

        <h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">Red-Teaming the Bumpers</span=
></h2>
        <p>The core recommendation of this piece is to build out and deploy=
 the
            potential bumpers that have already been explored in some depth=
 in past research. However, as a major
            secondary priority, we should be testing them in situ and in co=
mbination, with a focus on ensuring that no
            plausible model could circumvent the full suite.</p>
        <p>This would entail red-teaming exercises in the spirit of the Con=
trol agenda=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/MbWWKbyD5g=
LhJgfwn/meta-level-adversarial-evaluation-of-oversight-techniques-1">meta-l=
evel
                adversarial evaluations</a>: Here, =E2=80=98red-team=E2=80=
=99 researchers=E2=80=94who have full knowledge of the set of bumpers
            that a model will face=E2=80=94aim to produce an intentionally-=
misaligned model variant that is optimized to be as
            likely as possible to survive all of the bumpers while still ul=
timately taking some (fake)
            severely-misaligned action. If these researchers succeed, that =
calls into question the adequacy of the
            bumpers, and likely indicates ways they can be improved. If the=
se researchers fail, though, this gives only
            indirect and contingent positive evidence for safety, since the=
 space of possible misaligned models is
            large.</p><br><br><br>

        <h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">Related Agendas: Model Organi=
sms and Control</span></h2>
        <p>The <a href=3D"https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/ChDH335ckdvp=
xXaXX/model-organisms-of-misalignment-the-case-for-a-new-pillar-of-1">Model
                Organisms of Misalignment</a>&nbsp;agenda aims to intention=
ally develop and test misaligned models in order
            to understand how misalignment might emerge. This is a natural =
basic-research companion to Bumpers: Model
            organisms are an ideal input to the red-teaming exercises descr=
ibed above and evidence from work with model
            organisms help us make better guesses about where to strengthen=
 the bumpers and where correlated failures
            across bumpers could be possible. In the other direction, each =
time we hit a bumper and encounter warning
            signs for misalignment in the real world, that can feed back in=
to our decisions about which model organisms
            to build and study.</p>
        <p>The <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.06942">AI Control</a>&=
nbsp;agenda aims to build model-external safeguards
            that could let us to use an <span style=3D"font-style: italic;"=
>arbitrarily misaligned</span>&nbsp;model without
            giving it the opportunity to cause severe harm. Bumpers also ca=
lls for model-external safeguards and
            monitoring and will likely entail some of the same work in prac=
tice. But Bumpers is more oriented toward
            gathering and responding to evidence about the actual degree to=
 which a model is aligned and contemplates
            the possibility of building safeguards more selectively in resp=
onse to that evidence. Bumpers thus
            represents a distinct bet on the premises that alignment is rea=
sonably likely to be both tractable and
            necessary.</p><br><br><br>

        <h2>Limitations</h2>
        <h3>Selection Pressure and Iteration Limits</h3>
        <p>Each time we go through the core loop of catching a warning sign=
 for misalignment, adjusting our training
            strategy to try to avoid it, and training again, we are applyin=
g a bit of selection pressure against our
            bumpers. If we go through many such loops and only then, finall=
y, see a model that can make it through
            without hitting our bumpers, we should worry that it=E2=80=99s =
still dangerously misaligned and that we have
            inadvertently selected for a model that can evade the bumpers.<=
/p>
        <p>How severe of a problem this is depends on the quality and diver=
sity of the bumpers. (It also depends,
            unfortunately, on your prior beliefs about how likely misalignm=
ent is, which renders quantitative estimates
            here pretty uncertain.) If you=E2=80=99ve built excellent imple=
mentations of <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">all</span>&nbsp;of the bu=
mpers listed above, it=E2=80=99s plausible that you can run this
            loop thousands of times without meaningfully undermining their =
effectiveness.<sup><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/=
#ftnt8" id=3D"ftnt_ref8">[8]</a></sup>&nbsp;If you=E2=80=99ve only implemen=
ted two or three, and you=E2=80=99re unlucky, even a
            handful of iterations could lead to failure.</p>
        <h3>Ambiguous Findings</h3>
        <p>Unfortunately, not all warning signs will come with smoking-gun =
evidence that the model would have caused
            harm if given the opportunity: In behavioral evaluations, there=
 is no crisp distinction between errors and
            intentional
            patterns of bad behavior. White-box tests involve some lossines=
s when bridging the divide between complex
            model internals and high-level concepts like <span style=3D"fon=
t-style: italic;">goal</span>. </p>
        <p>A warning sign warrants a reaction if it causes well-informed ex=
perts to believe that the model is less well
            aligned than expected or that it has a non-negligible chance of=
 being severely misaligned. These judgment
            calls will have to be responsive to the broader competitive and=
 regulatory landscape: It is prudent to
            investigate more risks, and to investigate them more deeply, if=
 you have reasonable assurances that other
            actors aren=E2=80=99t already taking much greater risks.</p>
        <h3>No Free Lunch</h3>
        <p>It is possible, and consistent with all of the above, that adequ=
ately aligning a human-expert-level model is
            enormously slow and expensive. The Bumpers approach is still pl=
ausibly the most efficient strategy in this
            case, but it doesn=E2=80=99t save us from having to put in the =
work: It may be the case that our first warning signs
            of misalignment make it clear that the most promising alignment=
 strategies require huge amounts of compute
            or data, or that each =E2=80=98bounce=E2=80=99 will involve dis=
carding large parts of an expensive tuning run and starting
            over.</p>
        <p>For this plan to succeed under these conditions, it=E2=80=99s st=
ill necessary that the competitive and regulatory
            landscape allows developers to take however much time is needed=
 to make early AGI systems demonstrably safe.
        </p>
        <h3 id=3D"ceil">Hitting the Capability Ceiling</h3>
        <p>As AI capabilities move beyond the =E2=80=98early AGI=E2=80=99 r=
egime I contemplate here, the two key assumptions behind the
            bumpers strategy are likely to start to fail.</p>
        <p>With systems that are substantially superhuman at reasoning, ali=
gnment will likely become less tractable with
            existing methods, as the challenges motivating <a href=3D"https=
://www.anthropic.com/research/measuring-progress-on-scalable-oversight-for-=
large-language-models">scalable
                oversight</a>&nbsp;research start to bite. This should make=
 us less confident that the core loop of this
            process will terminate: It may take deeper new research to work=
 out how to align these systems. </p>
        <p>Similarly, with systems that are substantially superhuman at rea=
soning <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">about AI safety</span>, it becom=
es more plausible that they discover exotic
            ways of evading bumpers that no human adversarial evaluation co=
uld have caught. This should make us less
            confident that if the core loop of this process <span style=3D"=
font-style: italic;">does </span>terminate,
            that this means that the resulting model is in fact aligned. Es=
timating when we have reached this point is
            not trivial, but ordinary capability assessments, red-teaming e=
xercises, and warning signs from earlier
            model generations will all give us substantial evidence with wh=
ich to make this determination.</p>
        <p>Fortunately, once we=E2=80=99re in this higher-capability regime=
, we will likely already have access to early AGI
            systems that should (with some preparation) be able to automate=
 significant parts of AI safety R&amp;D at the
            level of human experts. If we use these agents well, as in the =
<a href=3D"https://openai.com/index/introducing-superalignment/">automated =
alignment researcher</a>&nbsp;strategy,
            it becomes much more plausible that we=E2=80=99re able to accel=
erate progress on safety across the board, giving us
            a wider range of options with which to address these challenges=
.</p><br><br><br>

        <h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">Conclusion</span></h2>
        <p>To get through the transition to superhuman AI, we=E2=80=99ll li=
kely need to delegate important tasks to
            circa-human-level automated researchers. If those automated res=
earchers are misaligned in a way that leads
            them to sabotage our work=E2=80=94or do any of the other harmfu=
l things that models at this capability level could
            do=E2=80=94the outlook is poor. So, we need to be able to align=
 these automated researchers.</p>
        <p>But it seems unlikely that we=E2=80=99ll have a robust understan=
ding of how to align models with these capabilities
            in time: Our depth of understanding will probably&nbsp;look mor=
e like today=E2=80=99s ML engineering than today=E2=80=99s
            aerospace engineering, which is to say that we won=E2=80=99t be=
 very confident in what we're doing. Given the
            potential stakes, this is a humbling and disconcerting state of=
 affairs, but it=E2=80=99s one that we shouldn=E2=80=99t look
            away from.</p>
        <p>Instead of aiming to get toward the aerospace end of the spectru=
m=E2=80=94a project that has little hope of paying
            out if things move quickly=E2=80=94I propose that we accept tha=
t our&nbsp;early AGI alignment work is very likely to
            depend critically on trial and error, and put up as many mechan=
isms as possible=E2=80=94the bumpers=E2=80=94to help us
            identify and respond to those errors. With an ambitious but fea=
sible effort there, I think we=E2=80=99ll be able to
            muddle through.</p><br><br><br>

        <h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">Come Help</span></h3>
        <p>Anthropic is committed to investing seriously in the kinds of me=
asures described here, and we=E2=80=99re eagerly
            hiring. The more excellent engineers and researchers there are =
who can contribute to this work, the
            faster
            we can move, the more we can publish, and the less likely we ar=
e to have to triage away more ambitious
            bets.
            If you think you=E2=80=99d be able to contribute, have a look a=
t <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/jobs">our
                jobs
                page</a>.</p>
        <p>Within the Alignment Science umbrella, I=E2=80=99m setting up a =
new team&nbsp;to productionize and professionalize the
            hands-on work of testing models for AGI-relevant forms of misal=
ignment.&nbsp;Elsewhere in Alignment Science,
            we
            recently founded a new Cognitive Oversight research team under =
Sam Marks that=E2=80=99s aiming to improve upon,
            test, and better understand the sorts of assessment methods we =
used in our recent <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/auditing-h=
idden-objectives">Auditing paper</a>. We are
            continuing to hire for our Model Organisms and Control teams to=
 continue to advance the related agendas
            described above.</p>
        <p>Beyond Alignment Science, Anthropic=E2=80=99s implementation of =
the agenda laid out here also depends directly on
            work that=E2=80=99s happening on Interpretability, Safeguards, =
Finetuning, and the Frontier Red Team. All of
            these
            teams are actively hiring.</p>
    </d-article><d-appendix style=3D"background: hsla(40,20%,30%,0.05);" id=
=3D"appendix">



        <h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">Acknowledgments</span></h2>
        <p>I'm grateful to the following for discussions that informed this=
 essay: Holden Karnofsky, Sam Marks, Fabien
            Roger, Evan Hubinger, Hoagy Cunningham, Akbir Khan, Chris
            Olah, Stuart Ritchie, Misha Wagner, Jan Leike, Joe Carlsmith, B=
uck Shlegeris, Ryan Greenblatt, Rohin
            Shah, and participants at the Summit for Existential Security. =
These opinions are my own.</p>

        <h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 600;">Notes</span></h2>
        <div>
            <p><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftn=
t_ref1" id=3D"ftnt1">[1]</a>&nbsp;In the language of <a href=3D"https://sle=
epinyourhat.github.io/checklist/">The
                    Checklist</a>, we need to be well prepared for Chapter =
2 before it starts. In the language of <a href=3D"https://ai-2027.com/">AI =
2027</a>, we need to adequately align the first model with the
                capabilities of Agent-3.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
            <p><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftn=
t_ref2" id=3D"ftnt2">[2]</a>&nbsp;These delays can be costly even from a po=
int of view that is
                focused
                very
                heavily on catastrophic misalignment risk: If we are slow t=
o trust early AGI systems and aren=E2=80=99t willing
                to
                use them in important R&amp;D contexts, we may miss opportu=
nities to better prepare for to align future,
                much
                more superhuman, AI systems for which alignment could be no=
ntrivial. </p>
        </div>
        <div>
            <p><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftn=
t_ref3" id=3D"ftnt3">[3]</a>&nbsp;See, for example, Ryan Greenblatt=E2=80=
=99s discussion of Debate in =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://redwoodresearch.su=
bstack.com/p/notes-on-handling-non-concentrated">Notes on handling
                    non-concentrated failures</a>=E2=80=9D.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
            <p><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftn=
t_ref4" id=3D"ftnt4">[4]</a>&nbsp;See, for example, the Execute/Replace/Aud=
it protocol from Buck
                Shelgeris <a href=3D"https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/j=
g3PuE3fYL9jq9zHB/win-continue-lose-scenarios-and-execute-replace-audit">her=
e</a>.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div>
            <p><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftn=
t_ref5" id=3D"ftnt5">[5]</a>&nbsp;Evidence that might call a suite of bumpe=
rs into question could
                include: Finding
                via white-box methods that the model is reasoning pretty ca=
refully about how to evade multiple of our
                black
                box methods. Finding models that clearly defect in some hon=
eypot environments but look benign to our
                white-box methods even as they're doing so, suggesting that=
 they're evading those methods. Finding
                warning
                signs for phenomena like Paul Christiano's <a href=3D"https=
://ai-alignment.com/training-robust-corrigibility-ce0e0a3b9b4d">RSA-2048 pr=
oblem</a>,
                wherein
                models are sensitive to evidence about the date or other at=
tributes of their situation that we aren=E2=80=99t
                able
                to spoof.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
            <p><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftn=
t_ref6" id=3D"ftnt6">[6]</a>&nbsp;Claude 3.7 can nonetheless be frustrating=
 to use as a coding
                agent
                because of
                related forms of shortcut-seeking behavior. We deemed it wo=
rth releasing on net, but we see ways to
                mitigate
                these issues significantly better in future releases.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
            <p><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftn=
t_ref7" id=3D"ftnt7">[7]</a>&nbsp;To be clear, it is crucially important th=
at we be very good at
                eliciting
                excellent behavior <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">at o=
r slightly above the level of human experts
                </span>on tasks related to AGI safety R&amp;D. My expectati=
on is that ordinary R&amp;D incentives will lead to a
                great deal of progress on this kind of elicitation in gener=
al, such that applying it to AGI safety will
                be,
                while not trivial, fairly straightforward. If this is not t=
he direction the field takes=E2=80=94if, for example,
                it
                turns out that capabilities progress is increasingly driven=
 by narrow domain-specific investment rather
                than
                general improvements=E2=80=94then AGI safety R&amp;D capabi=
lities elicitation could become a top priority on par
                with
                anything else here.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
            <p><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/bumpers/#ftn=
t_ref8" id=3D"ftnt8">[8]</a>&nbsp;Though, of course, it will be hard to be =
highly confident in
                this.
                Realistically, the more iterations we need to make, the mor=
e desirable it is to <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">find new bumpers <=
/span>that we can introduce late in the process as
                additional checks.</p>
        </div>
    </d-appendix>


